04731nam a22007095i 9780814709061DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20032003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147090617 a10.18574/97808147090612doi  a(DE-B1597)546917  a(OCoLC)782877909  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE185.86 .B649 2002 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a306.48409731 aBoyd, Todd, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New H.N.I.C. :bThe Death of Civil Rights and the Reign of Hip Hop /cTodd Boyd. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Who We Be: Introducin' the New H.N.I.C. -- t1. No Time for Fake Niggas -- t2. Brothas Gonna Work It Out -- t3. Can't Knock the Hustle -- t4. Head Nigga in Charge -- tEpilogue -- tSelected Bibliography -- tGlossary of Hip Hop Terms -- tShout Outs -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Lauryn Hill stepped forward to accept her fifth Grammy Award in 1999, she paused as she collected the last trophy, and seeming somewhat startled said, "This is crazy, 'cause this is hip hop music.'" Hill's astonishment at receiving mainstream acclaim for music once deemed insignificant testifies to the explosion of this truly revolutionary art form. Hip hop music and the culture that surrounds it-film, fashion, sports, and a whole way of being-has become the defining ethos for a generation. Its influence has spread from the state's capital to the nation's capital, from the Pineapple to the Big Apple, from 'Frisco to Maine, and then on to Spain. But moving far beyond the music, hip hop has emerged as a social and cultural movement, displacing the ideas of the Civil Rights era. Todd Boyd maintains that a new generation, having grown up in the aftermath of both Civil Rights and Black Power, rejects these old school models and is instead asserting its own values and ideas. Hip hop is distinguished in this regard because it never attempted to go mainstream, but instead the mainstream came to hip hop.The New H.N.I.C., like hip hop itself, attempts to keep it real, and challenges conventional wisdom on a range of issues, from debates over use of the "N-word," the comedy of Chris Rock, and the "get money" ethos of hip hop moguls like Sean "P. Diddy" Combs and Russell Simmons, to hip hop's impact on a diverse array of figures from Bill Clinton and Eminem to Jennifer Lopez.Maintaining that Martin Luther King, Jr.'s "I Have a Dream" speech is less important today than DMX's It's Dark and Hell is Hot, Boyd argues that Civil Rights as a cultural force is dead, confined to a series of media images frozen in another time. Hip hop, on the other hand, represents the vanguard, and is the best way to grasp both our present and future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aAfrican American youthxPolitical activity. 0aAfrican American youthxSocial conditions. 0aAfrican American youthxSocial life and customs. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsy1975- 0aHip-hop. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814709061423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814709061.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE 